text:
It arrived quickly was easy to set up so within days of ordering I began putting this small wonder to the test. I ran every cycle, did different types of loads, and it leaked, it leaked every run, no matter how much water was in it. Undaunted, I mopped up after it and continued. My clothes came out clean, fresh and were spun so well it only took them a half day to dry hung indoors. Then I did a load of sweaters, the lint trap filled up, I cleared it and followed it with blankets and that was it, it choked. Unable to drain I could hear the motor running but the tub wouldnt clear. So i emptied it, unhooked the tubes underneath and let it drain that way. Darn it. I contacted Panda and they said “junk it we'll replace it”. Impressive. OK of they are willing to stand by their product Im willing to give it another try. A little wiser this time. The “new” one has yet to leak. Cut to less than six months later tge second one is dead. First off I thought it was great that they sent me another one, but it was used. The tub had a cut in it and the motor was broke from its base but I figured if it ran, “whatever”.
These machines are great when they run, they run well. The clothes come out clean and nearly dry. But the water pumps are tiny and clearly too small. I dont think its worth $275 which is about what I paid for it.
PS. They sent me a new/refurbished water pump. I spliced it in after I couldnt get the wires to pull out. And its running again. Now Im trying to run loads 6L and under and have asked my roomie bot to run the spun cycle repeatedly since its not Necessary and it engages the water pump. I'm hoping if I take it easy on the water pump the rest will hold up. Fingers Crossed! I also found some water pumps for it online and pump them away for backup. text: When your dishwasher starts leaking water, you gotta get it fixed. The OEM Whirlpool item was triple the price and a week+ for delivery, so I went with this cheaper model with 1-day delivery through Amazon. Installation was pretty straight forward if your have any DIY/handyman skills.  But it seems like our dishwasher is louder now, in that we hear a more pronounced water swishing and washing - I don't know if its a coincidence, or we're just more aware of it, or if this diverter valve and motor don't quite line up like the original. But it works. Time will tell how long it lasts (it was not as well built/sturdy as the OEM that seems to use thicker plastic). Additionally, when installing the rubber grommet, it felt loose when fitted in place, so I took it back out, put a thin bead of silicone sealant around the outside edge, fitted it back in place and let it sit overnight to dry. The next day I finished the installation and it has not leaked.  Looking back, I probably could have just replaced that grommet to fix the leak, but I couldn't be sure if the grommet was leaking or if water was leaking through the water diverter motor, so I replaced both so that I wouldn't have to re-do the job.

We had to remove the whole inner back panel of the dryer that the wheels are mounted on so that you can remove the nuts off the original wheels easier. Also, use a metric socket wrench because we only had wrenches 1/2” (too small) and 9/16” (too big) and ended up using vise-grip pliers and it was very hard to loosen the original wheels nut and the vise grips still was deforming the nut. title: Very sturdy & well made hat washer
text:
I have an existing hat washer from another brand. I wanted to get another one so that I could wash 2 caps at the same time. I saw this available via the Vine program. I placed the order and it was delivered within 2 days.

Here's my initial impressions of the new one (black) vs the old one (white)
- The new hat washer is much more robust & sturdy, quality is better than the old one
- The new hat washer comes in 3 parts; the old one with 2 pieces
- Even though it appears that you could wash 2 hats simultaneously with the new hat washer, it's recommended to wash only 1 at a time
- The multiple latch points of the new hat washer secures the hat better than the old one; this greatly reduces the risk of the hat washer unexpectedly opening up in the dishwasher
- The new hat washer is slightly longer than the old one (0.50 inch); this may or may not make a difference when placing it in the dishwasher
- The double-sided instructions that accompany the new hat washer are very clear & helpful; the insert for the old hat washer had a few lines that didn't really say much
- Both hat washers work very well in the dishwasher
- The new hat washer can be used in a washing machine on gentle cycle. I haven't tried it yet, but will do so soon; I would never even attempt to use the old hat washer in a washing machine

Overall, I think this new hat washer is great. It's definitely better than the one I already had. I have more flexibility when it comes to washing hats (washing machine vs dishwasher). And now I can wash 2 hats at the same time.

The bad: after 1.5 years, I noticed some deformation near the top, then found a hole. I took apart the machine and found two holes (see attached pics). It looks like the rubber degraded---I see small bits of rubber near the two holes.

Notes: this includes a drain port on the bottom, but no ports on the top (what look like ports in the picture are sealed off). My original door boot never developed holes---I replaced it after 10 years after I noticed lots of bacteria/mold growth around the drain port (partly because I didn't realize how much cleaning was necessary after each wash).

So, this did a decent job of extending the life of my LG washer for an additional 1.5 years. But, it's pretty disappointing that it would degrade so quickly. I might still buy the same one as a replacement since it's inexpensive and I'm used to doing the repair now.

Tip: if you are doing the repair yourself, *do* buy yourself the spring expansion tool. The alternative is to attach zip-ties to both ends of the spring, but having the extra hand available to set the wire in place while holding the spring open is invaluable and saved me a ton of frustration on the 2nd try. title: Great Ice Machine!
text:
I got this countertop ice machine for some outdoor entertaining, and for in the garage. I spend a lot of time in my garage and always have to come back in the house to refresh my beverage. Having cold drinks in my minifridge and and ice machine makes it so much easier. And, I don't dirty up the house as much, trapsing in and out.

Here are my observations about this machine:

It works by chilling the stainless steel 'tray' and running water over it. As the water gets colder it freezes in the tray. After the tray reaches a cold enough temperature, that signals the machine that the trays is full of ice. The system pauses and the ice drops into the bin. The next cycle begins.

1. I really like the way it is designed. I understand the tech inside it and am very impressed with how well it works. It is so capable, yet so compact. The fit and finish of all the components equals that of commercial machines. Very well made.

2. I like how quickly it produces ice. After I filled the tank with room temperature water, it was about 20 minutes until it dumped the first 'tray' of cubes. That load was not as well formed as the subsequent loads. But, it was good enough to ice down four tall glasses of tea. Then, it continued to pump out a new 'tray' about every 15 minutes. Each tray being better than the last. About half way through that first gallon of water, it was chilled enough that the cubes were completely formed and crystal clear.

3. I like the quantity of ice that one tank of water will produce. As you can see in one of my pictures, I have two 1 gallon storage bags full of ice, all from one tank.

4. I like the convenience. Not just about having an ice machine where I want it. But, also for the filling options. You can either fill the tank manually, and / or place up to a 2.5 gallon water jug on top for continuous operation. (The instructions really didn't go into the jug option. But, all you do is leave the black jug adapter plate in place. You have to lift it off, to manually fill the tank.) There is a trip plate in the ice collection bin that will stop operation, once the bin is full.

I really look forward to the warmer months, when I can be outside more, in the garage more and have cold, iced beverages on hand, thanks to this Silonn countertop ice machine.

title: It WORKS
text:
When I had a small leak in my 30-plus-year old dishwasher, I looked at appliance repair parts sites for a replacement gasket. They were priced at $70 and more, but every site said they were NO LONGER AVAILABLE. So I measured the length and width of my dishwasher door and ordered one that was as close to the size. On-line videos showed how to do the job, but they were for newer dishwashers and not exactly accurate as for my dishwasher.

I installed the new gasket starting at the bottom corners where the cutouts are in the gasket. My dishwasher has no marker for the center of the door at the top, and the gasket had nothing to show what was the middle. I ended up with an excess at the top, and I cut it there. Then I calculated how much to cut off by aligning the two ends. The amount turned out to be about 3/4 inch. I had thought I would use silicone sealant at the joint, but that was not really necessary since the gasket ends butted together perfectly. NOTE: To get one bottom side into place properly, I had to remove a couple of the screws holding the door liner so I could lift the liner enough to get the gasket into the track.

The two corner baffles were also replaced. I removed the old ones and thoroughly cleaned the areas where the baffles were to be placed. They just LIFT OUT, and the new baffles just have to be placed in the corners and pressed down so they will fit.

The bottom of the gasket has a gap between the ends, just like my old gasket. Some people are selling gap covers, but that is not necessary in this case. Also, when I asked if this gasket would fit my old dishwasher, I was told it did not, and I was told I should visit their on-line stores. The problem with that was they don't have any way of determining whether the gasket would fit any dishwasher model number. Upsell?

After replacing the gasket and baffles, I closed the dishwasher door with some effort since the gasket is new. Without any dishes or dishwashing detergent in the dishwasher, I ran the washer through a complete cycle. I had a towel on the floor under the dishwasher – just in case. Everything went as smooth as possible.

title: It just works
text:
The design by the dishwasher manufacturer makes this part susceptible to breaking because the end with the single hole / eyelet attaches to a bolt head, and the cable bends about 90 degrees to where it goes over the plastic / nylon pulley wheel. That pulley wheel has no groove for the cable, and I am surprised it has lasted all these years.

Starting the job requires removing several screws holding the two bottom cover panels - two screws on each end in my application. Then you have access to the broken cable. It's unlikely that both cables would break at the same time since one will break causing the springs to let go - and the door will be heavy.

The 2 springs that support most of the weight of the door are attached to the other end that has 2 holes. Two cables are required, and both probably should be replaced at the same time.

Once those springs are attached to the cables, the eyelet ends can be slipped over the bolt heads. The first is simple to attach, but it has to have some tension on it so it does not slip off the pulley wheel while attaching the other end. Stretching the springs is best done using some tool - maybe a locking pliers - and wearing leather work gloves to prevent hurting your hands when it slips. That is the hardest part of this procedure ... more than standing on your head to replace the screws when reattaching the two bottom cover panels.

This is the part that has been breaking about every 5 years on my model dishwasher. At 29 years of age, the dishwasher may be replaced the next time this cable breaks. Hopefully the next model will be designed better and won't require this continued replacement.
